"Cai M., Shin C.-S., Van Den Dool H.M., Wang W., Saha S., Kumar A.","The role of long-term trends in seasonal predictions: Implication of global warming in the NCEP CFS",2009,"Weather and Forecasting","24","4",,"965","973",,,10.1175/2009WAF2222231.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70350008313&partnerID=40&md5=b9d6e23ae713e2f5970f50ffcf58b52f","Department of Meteorology, The Florida State University, Tallahassee, Florida, United States; NOAA/NWS/NCEP/Climate Prediction Center, Camp Springs, Maryland, United States; NOAA/NWS/NCEP/Environmental Modeling Center, Camp Springs, Maryland, United States; NOAA/NWS/NCEP/Climate Prediction Center, Camp Springs, Maryland, United States","Cai, M., Department of Meteorology, The Florida State University, Tallahassee, Florida, United States; Shin, C.-S., Department of Meteorology, The Florida State University, Tallahassee, Florida, United States; Van Den Dool, H.M., NOAA/NWS/NCEP/Climate Prediction Center, Camp Springs, Maryland, United States; Wang, W., NOAA/NWS/NCEP/Climate Prediction Center, Camp Springs, Maryland, United States; Saha, S., NOAA/NWS/NCEP/Environmental Modeling Center, Camp Springs, Maryland, United States; Kumar, A., NOAA/NWS/NCEP/Climate Prediction Center, Camp Springs, Maryland, United States","This paper analyzes long-term surface air temperature trends in a 25-yr (1982-2006) dataset of retrospective seasonal climate predictions made by the NCEP Climate Forecast System (CFS), a model that has its atmospheric greenhouse gases fixed at the 1988 concentration level. Although the CFS seasonal forecasts tend to follow the observed interannual variability very closely, there exists a noticeable time-dependent discrepancy between the CFS forecasts and observations, with a warm model bias before 1988 and a cold bias afterward except for a short-lived warm bias during 1992-94. The trend from warm to cold biases is likely caused by not including the observed increase in the anthropogenic greenhouse gases in the CFS, whereas the warm bias in 1992-94 reflects the absence of the anomalous aerosols released by the 1991 Mount Pinatubo eruption. Skill analysis of the CFS seasonal climate predictions with and without the warming trend suggests that the 1997-98 El Nin{ogonek}o event contributes significantly to the record-breaking global warmth in 1998 whereas the record-breaking warm decade since 2000 is mainly due to the effects of the increased greenhouse gases. Implications for operational seasonal prediction will be discussed. © 2009 American Meteorological Society.",,"Anthropogenic greenhouse gas; Atmospheric greenhouse; Climate forecasts; Concentration levels; Data sets; Interannual variability; Long-term trend; Mount Pinatubo eruption; Seasonal climate prediction; Seasonal forecasts; Seasonal prediction; Surface air temperatures; Time-dependent; Aerosols; Climatology; Gas fuel analysis; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Greenhouses; Nickel compounds; Weather forecasting; Climate models; air temperature; climate prediction; data set; El Nino; global warming; greenhouse gas; observational method; surface temperature; time dependent behavior; weather forecasting; Central Luzon; Luzon; Mount Pinatubo; Philippines; Zambales; Pinatubo",,,,,,"Behringer, D.W., Xue, Y., Evaluation of the Global Ocean Data Assimilation System at NCEP: The Pacific Ocean Eighth Symp. on Integrated Observing and Assimilation Systems for Atmosphere, Oceans, and Land Surface, 2004. , http://ams.confex.com/ams/pdfpapers/70720.pdf, Preprints, Seattle, WA, Amer. Meteor. Soc., 2.3. [Available online at]; Cai, M., Kalnay, E., Can reanalysis have anthropogenic climate trends without model forcing? (2005) J Climate, 18, pp. 1844-1849; Cox, P., Stephenson, D., A changing climate for prediction (2007) Science, 317, pp. 207-208. , doi:10.1126/science.1145956; Doblas-Reyes, F.J., Hagedorn, R., Palmer, T.N., Morcrette, J.-J., Impact of increasing greenhouse gas concentration in seasonal ensemble forecas